      "content": "# Night of the Living Dead\n\n## Logline\nWhen the dead begin to rise and attack the living, a group of strangers barricades themselves in an isolated farmhouse for a desperate night of survival against impossible odds.\n\n## Synopsis\nA nationwide epidemic of reanimated corpses transforms an ordinary night into a fight for survival. When a young woman and her brother encounter a ghoul in a cemetery, a brutal chain of events forces them to flee to an isolated farmhouse. There, they meet a resourceful truck driver and a fractured family already sheltering inside. As the undead siege intensifies and a nationwide emergency unfolds on television, the group's resolve fractures under pressure. Desperation leads to violence among the survivors themselves—infighting that proves as deadly as the threat outside. By dawn, when armed rescuers finally arrive to contain the epidemic, the cost of the night has been paid in full.\n\n## Film Identity\n- **Genre:** Horror, Thriller\n- **Format:** Feature Film\n- **Setting:** Contemporary 1960s\n- **Tone:** Bleak, relentless horror\n- **Runtime estimate:** 86 minutes\n\n## Themes\n\n**Survivalism vs Panic**\nThe film explores how survival instinct can erode into chaos when fear takes hold. Ben's pragmatic leadership clashes with the group's mounting hysteria—the failed escape attempt with Tom epitomizes how panic sabotages even the most rational plans.\n\n**Breakdown of Social Order**\nWithin the house, civilized cooperation crumbles into brutality. Harry and Ben's violent conflict, culminating in a fatal shooting, demonstrates how quickly human hierarchies collapse when social structures fail and basic shelter becomes the only law.\n\n**Futility and Nihilism**\nNo action matters. Ben survives the night only to be executed by rescuers; Karen's resurrection ensures her parents' deaths; the nationwide ghoul epidemic frames individual heroism as meaningless. The film offers no redemption, only the relentless grinding down of hope.\n\n## Comparable Films\n\n- **The Twilight Zone: \"Midnight Sun\" (1960)** — A claustrophobic, idea-driven nightmare with minimal resources and maximum dread; the focus on ordinary people facing extraordinary, inescapable circumstances.\n\n- **Invasion of the Body Snatchers (1956)** — The creeping sense that familiar society is being consumed by an alien force; paranoia about who can be trusted and where safety truly lies.\n\n- **The Thing (1982)** — A confined group under siege, fractured by internal distrust; the realization that the real threat may be the people standing next to you, not the enemy outside.\n\n- **Dawn of the Dead (1978)** — The spiritual successor that deepens the social commentary; survival reduced to a mechanical act, stripped of meaning or hope.\n\n## Scope at a Glance\n\n- **Total scenes:** 13\n- **Unique locations:** 5\n- **Principal cast:** 8\n- **Exterior scenes:** 5\n- **Night shoots:** 10\n- **VFX/FX scenes:** 12\n- **Complexity read:** Contained, single-location siege film with a small ensemble cast and heavy reliance on practical effects, makeup, and gunplay. The majority of the story unfolds across one night in and around a farmhouse, minimizing logistical scale while maximizing emotional intensity.",
